{"id":"1603.02413","submitter":"Pascal Held","authors":"Pascal Held, Benjamin Krause, Rudolf Kruse","title":"Dynamic Clustering in Social Networks using Louvain and Infomap Method","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.SI physics.soc-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Finding communities or clusters in social networks is a fa- mous topic in\nsocial network analysis. Most algorithms are limited to static snapshots, so\nthey cannot handle dynamics within the underlying graph. In this paper we\npresent a modification of the Louvain community detec- tion method to handle\nchanges in the graph without rerunning the full algorithm. Also, we adapted the\nLouvain greedy approach to optimize the Infomap measure. The main idea is, to\nrecalculate only a small area around the changes. Depending on the graph size\nand the amount of changes, this yields a massive runtime decrease. As\nvalidation data, we provide a graph generator, which produces spe- cific\ncommunity structures, at given times and also intermediate steps to transform\nthe graph from one to another specific graph. Experiments show that runtime\ndecrease is possible without much loss of quality. These values depend on the\nreprocessed area inside the graph.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 8 Mar 2016 08:28:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-09"}
